  "prompt": "Can a set be both a subset and a proper subset?",
  "response": "In set theory, a set \\( A \\) is considered a subset of another set \\( B \\) if every element of \\( A \\) is also an element of \\( B \\). This is denoted as \\( A \\subseteq B \\). A set \\( A \\) is considered a proper subset of \\( B \\) (denoted \\( A \\subset B \\)) if \\( A \\subseteq B \\) and \\( A \\neq B \\), meaning \\( A \\) must be strictly contained within \\( B \\) such that there is at least one element in \\( B \\) that is not in \\( A \\).\n\nTherefore, a set can be a subset and a proper subset under specific conditions. However, a set being both a subset and a proper subset of the same set is not possible if it is referring to the same relationship with another set. For example, if \\( A = \\{1, 2\\} \\) and \\( B = \\{1, 2, 3\\} \\), then \\( A \\subseteq B \\) and \\( A \\subset B \\), so \\( A \\) is a subset and a proper subset of \\( B \\). Conversely, if we consider a set \\( C \\) such that \\( C = \\{1, 2\\} \\), it is true that \\( C \\subseteq C \\) as every set is a subset of itself, but \\( C \\) is not a proper subset of itself because it is not true that \\( C \\neq C \\).\n\nIn summary, while a set can be a subset and a proper subset of different sets (or in relation to different comparisons), it cannot be both a subset and a proper subset of the same set when considered under the same relational context.",
